726058f-a.text:
Astoria, Queens: Shown is a general view of Astoria, looking southwestward from the Triborough Bridge. The thoroughfare is 21st Street, running south from Hoyt Avenue. In the background is the Queensboro Bridge (left) and the Mid-Manhattan skyline.
P. L. Sperr  July 25, 1936

726067f-b.text:
Astoria Boulevard, between Third and First Streets, viewing northward aross the scrap metal dumps on the south side of the thoroughfare,toward the buildings on the north side. View three shows an old dwelling, probably dating back to pre-Revolutionary days. The vantage point is the shore of Hallets Cove.
P. L. Sperr  March 11, 1931

726102f-a.text:
Astoria Squsre -- point of intersection of Astoria Boulevard, 27th Avenue, Newtown Avenue, and 21st Street -- viewing west from where the Newtown Avenue trolley tracks (lower left corner) join those on Astoria Boulevard. The latter thoroughfare bends southwestward to the left of the four-story building; to the right is 27th
Avenue, running west from 21st Street.
P. L. Sperr  March 13, 1931

726093f-b.text:
Astoria Boulevard, north side, west from 88th Street, over Jacksons Mill Creek, and showing an old farmhouse nestling among the trees at 87th Street. This land is part
of the former Kouvenhoven estate.
P. L. Sperr  October 19, 1935

726088f-a.text:
Astoria Boulevard, south side, in the 75th Street line, showing a building of modern origin located on land belonging to
J. L. Riker from 1873 to 1896.
April 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726091f-a.text:
Astoria Boulevard, north side, between 79th and 80th Streets, showing the C. Luyster house of 1852, L. Douglas was the owner in
1873 and F. Conover in 1896.
April 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726092f-a.text:
Astoria Boulevard, north side, between 79th and 80th Streets, showing the A. R. Luyster farmhouse. It was owned by L. Douglas in 1873. The house is about 150 feet back of the Boulevard. Another Luyster house was located at what is now (1894) the southwest corner of Astoria Boulevard and 79th Street.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  April, 1923
